#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: re-anchor country labels to the visual center, not the widest row.

Mike: W. Sahara and Dem. Rep. Congo (and likely others) were landing at the
edge of the country instead of the middle - "maybe the widest part of the
country was the wrong call... find the closest point to the center where the
letters are clearly visible, especially the more one zooms in." Checked the
data: W. Sahara's widest row had perp=0.11 - a sliver right at the Mauritania
border, which the previous "maximize width" objective happily picked over any
better-centered spot, since it never considered position relative to center at
all.

New anchor logic per country: start from the pole of inaccessibility (the point
deepest inside the polygon, farthest from any edge or border - the standard
algorithm for "best point to label a polygon," same one Mapbox itself uses).
Use it directly if there is room there for the label. Only if that exact point
is pinched too tight does it look at a handful of nearby points in a small ring
around the center (never far away), taking the closest one that actually fits -
so a label can be nudged off dead-center for legibility, but never jumps across
the country chasing extra width the way the old objective did.

Sizes are left alone unless the chosen point cannot comfortably fit the existing
size, in which case it shrinks just enough to fit (floor of 7.0, same as before)
- most countries (212/242) keep their current size exactly, only repositioned.
Rotation stays 0 for everyone, untouched from the previous patch.
Idempotent, pure ASCII source.
Usage: python3 worldbook_label_central.py index.html index.html
"""
import sys, re

INP = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "index.html"
OUT = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "index.html"
text = open(INP, encoding="utf-8").read()

